1. An interface is a reference type and is similar to the class.

2. An interface is implicitly abstract.

3. Methods in an interface are implicitly public and abstract.

4. An interface can extend another interface

5. You cannot instantiate an interface.

6. An interface does not contain any constructors.

7. All of the methods in an interface are abstract.

8. An interface can extend multiple interfaces.

Functional Interface?

A Functional Interface is an interface that contains exactly ONE abstract method.
It enables lambda expressions and is the foundation of functional programming in Java

It can have:
    ✅ One abstract method
    ✅ Multiple default methods
    ✅ Multiple static methods
    ❌ More than one abstract method

What is @FunctionalInterface Annotation?

    @FunctionalInterface
    interface Test {
        void run();
    }

This annotation:
- Ensures interface has only ONE abstract method
